I really want to understand what the fuss is about with Scala so I fired up a REPL and found a tutorial and went to work. Then I can across this:<p><pre><code>    scala> print(&quot;5&quot; + 5)
    55
</code></pre>
And I stopped there (for now). At least my C++ compiler will warn about that (although it will still compile even if it doesn&#x27;t print anything save for the newline):<p><pre><code>    #include <iostream>
    using namespace std;

    int main(int argc, char *argv[]) {
        cout << &quot;5&quot; + 5 << endl;
        return 0;
    }
</code></pre>
Python gives me a TypeError. And so does Common Lisp. I was expecting the same from Scala; a language which purports to be a multi-paradigm language with static type inference and a strong functional programming bias. Not even a warning.<p>What&#x27;s the reasoning behind this in Scala?
